## Overall Feedback

**Cash imputation and overlap moments**

A core component of the incidence analysis involves extrapolating cash moments from Clover using the two-part model in Appendix C. Because settlement data do not observe cash, readers will focus closely on how these imputed overlap moments are validated, particularly for the large firms that drive the attenuation results through negotiated discounts.

Appendix C.2.3 explicitly states that the sufficient-statistics exercise depends on second moments, but the current validation focuses on the mean cash share, overall standard deviation, and the fit of the conditional cash distribution. There appears to be a gap regarding revenue-weighted cash-card overlap moments by sector and firm size. This becomes highly relevant given that Table 1 shows Clover merchants have median annual sales of 0.09 million dollars, while Section III.B.3 emphasizes firms above 1 billion dollars, and Appendix C caps firm size at the Clover 99th percentile when predicting settlement cash shares. Unpacking direct validation or establishing bounds for these overlap moments across sectors and firm sizes would help secure the estimated 13.9 billion dollars cash loss and the 8.6 billion dollars sorting attenuation.

**Pass-through parameters**

The headline welfare estimates naturally depend on the assumptions governing price and reward pass-through. Section IV.A.2 applies full retail price pass-through, and Section IV.A.3 hard-codes full rewards pass-through, though Section I.A cites evidence pointing closer to 86% for rewards pass-through.

Table A.6 demonstrates that the precise pass-through values significantly alter the welfare distribution. For example, premium-credit gains shift from 18.2 billion dollars in the baseline to 0.5 billion dollars under a 70% reward pass-through, and branch to 30.4 billion dollars if price pass-through is 70% while rewards remain full. Given that incomplete pass-through exercises in the structural model still impose full rewards pass-through, and Appendix E relies on average ticket size as a noisy proxy for prices at restaurants, readers may scrutinize the centrality of these parameters. Since the paper's primary focus is consumer-to-consumer transfers rather than just aggregate merchant costs, elevating the partition between prices, consumer rewards, and issuer retention from an appendix sensitivity check to a foregrounded dynamic would clarify the paper's core mechanical bounds.

**The payment-to-income bridge**

The translation of payment-type incidence into income-group transfers involves a sequence of inference steps in Section V.B.3 and Appendix B.4. The current mapping integrates preferred in-person payment methods from the DCPC, ownership-based splits from MRI, reweighting to settlement shares, and a common purchases-to-income assumption to yield dollar magnitudes.

Several structural coding choices do significant work in this bridge: assigning all credit spending to premium if a household owns any premium card, splitting debit into regulated versus exempt strictly by the reported count of institutions, and substituting payment preference for actual expenditure shares. While the merchant data cleanly identifies transfers across payment instruments (as in Table 4), the transfer of 9.2 billion dollars from households below 150,000 dollars to those above relies heavily on these bridging assumptions. Modifying the text to either fortify the robustness of this income mapping or to center the analysis more firmly on the well-identified payment-type incidence could forestall concerns about how the regressivity claims are constructed.

**Framing the policy counterfactuals**

The transition from the sufficient-statistics framework to the evaluation of policy counterfactuals introduces a tension worth clarifying. The theorem is shown to be exact for small fee changes and is derived for fixed payment preferences (Sections IV.A.1 and IV.B; footnote 14), with the structural model allowing consumer reallocation across merchants but not across payment instruments.

Sections V.B-V.D apply this framework to evaluate discrete, large-scale changes: zero interchange, the Durbin Amendment, and premiumization. The introduction and conclusion distinctly frame the Durbin Amendment and premiumization as regressive. Because these specific policy environments are highly likely to trigger endogenous adjustments in card adoption, rewards menus, free-checking offsets, merchant acceptance, and steering, readers might question whether the model margins can hold fixed under such weight. Reframing these counterfactual exercises as partial-incidence decompositions isolating the mechanics holding payment mix fixed, rather than equilibrium policy evaluations, might be more defensible.

