### 2. Mathematical error in estimating the increase in total interchange fees

**Status**: [Pending]

**Quote**:
> Since the average interchange rate on premium cards is $2.1 \%$, compared to $1.7 \%$ for basic cards, this shift has raised total credit card interchange fees by roughly 20%.

**Feedback**:
The claim that the shift to premium cards has raised total credit card interchange fees by "roughly 20%" appears to contain a mathematical error regarding aggregate costs. As established in the text, the shift in premium card share was from 15% in 2006 to 60% in 2022. Assuming stable underlying rates of 1.7% for basic and 2.1% for premium cards, the initial average rate would be $0.15(2.1\%) + 0.85(1.7\%) = 1.76\%$, and the final average rate would be $0.60(2.1\%) + 0.40(1.7\%) = 1.94\%$. The percentage increase in the average credit card interchange fee (and thus total fees holding volume constant) is therefore $(1.94 - 1.76) / 1.76 \approx 10.2\%$. The \~20% figure presented in the text likely reflects the raw difference between the premium and basic rate tiers themselves $(2.1 - 1.7)/1.7 \approx 23.5\%$, but applying this growth factor to "total credit card interchange fees" overlooks the underlying baseline shares. Please adjust the phrasing so it accurately reflects either the aggregate effect ($\sim 10\%$) or clarifies that the 20% increase pertains strictly to the transaction volume that underwent the shift.

